<p>&nbsp;</p>";}i:77;a:5:{s:4:"guid";s:9:"Blog:4841";s:4:"link";s:70:"http://beatlesradio.com/the-beatles-50-years-ago-today-january-11-1968";s:5:"title";s:48:"The Beatles 50 Years Ago Today: January 11, 1968";s:11:"description";s:186:"<p><strong>The </strong><strong class="golden"> #1 song in the US</strong> on <strong class="golden">January 11, 1968</strong></p>
<h3 class="hidden-xs">Hello, Goodbye - The Beatles</h3>";s:7:"summary";s:186:"<p><strong>The </strong><strong class="golden"> #1 song in the US</strong> on <strong class="golden">January 11, 1968</strong></p>
<h3 class="hidden-xs">Hello, Goodbye - The Beatles</h3>";}i:78;a:5:{s:4:"guid";s:9:"Blog:4840";s:4:"link";s:70:"http://beatlesradio.com/the-beatles-50-years-ago-today-january-10-1968";s:5:"title";s:48:"The Beatles 50 Years Ago Today: January 10, 1968";s:11:"description";s:1381:"<h1 class="title single-title entry-title"><span style="font-size: 10pt;">Recording: Wonderwall Music by George Harrison</span></h1>
<p>EMI Recording Studio, Bombay, India<br />Producer: George Harrison<br />Engineers: JP Sen, SN Gupta</p>
<p>George Harrison had flown to India on 7 January 1968 to record the soundtrack for the film Wonderwall. The second session took place on this day.</p>
<p>The sessions began on 9 January in Bombay (Mumbai), and the soundtrack was mostly complete by 12 January.</p>
<p>On this day Harrison invited camera crews in to film proceedings. Reuters filmed around 45 seconds of colour footage, and BBC News shot slightly less. In the silent footage the musicians are believed to have been working on the track Fantasy Sequins.</p>
<p>The musicians included Ashish Khan (sarod), ahapurush Misra (tabla and pakavaj), Sharad Jadev and Hanuman Jadev (shanhais), Shambu-Das, Indril Bhattacharya and Shankar Ghosh (sitar), Chandra Shakher (sur-bahar), Shiv Kumar Sharmar (santorr), SR Kenkare and Hari Prasad Chaurasia (flute), Vinayak Vohra (taar shehnai) and Rijram Desad (dholak, harmonium and tabla-tarang).</p>
<p>The Bombay sessions took place at EMI Recording Studios, based at the Universal Insurance Building, Sir Pherozeshah Mehta Rd, Fort, Bombay 400001.</p>
<p><img src="/Content/Images/uploaded/2018_blog/jan10.jpg" alt="" width="100" /></p>";s:7:"summary";s:1381:"<h1 class="title single-title entry-title"><span style="font-size: 10pt;">Recording: Wonderwall Music by George Harrison</span></h1>
<p>EMI Recording Studio, Bombay, India<br />Producer: George Harrison<br />Engineers: JP Sen, SN Gupta</p>
<p>George Harrison had flown to India on 7 January 1968 to record the soundtrack for the film Wonderwall. The second session took place on this day.</p>
<p>The sessions began on 9 January in Bombay (Mumbai), and the soundtrack was mostly complete by 12 January.</p>
<p>On this day Harrison invited camera crews in to film proceedings. Reuters filmed around 45 seconds of colour footage, and BBC News shot slightly less. In the silent footage the musicians are believed to have been working on the track Fantasy Sequins.</p>
<p>The musicians included Ashish Khan (sarod), ahapurush Misra (tabla and pakavaj), Sharad Jadev and Hanuman Jadev (shanhais), Shambu-Das, Indril Bhattacharya and Shankar Ghosh (sitar), Chandra Shakher (sur-bahar), Shiv Kumar Sharmar (santorr), SR Kenkare and Hari Prasad Chaurasia (flute), Vinayak Vohra (taar shehnai) and Rijram Desad (dholak, harmonium and tabla-tarang).</p>
<p>The Bombay sessions took place at EMI Recording Studios, based at the Universal Insurance Building, Sir Pherozeshah Mehta Rd, Fort, Bombay 400001.</p>
<p><img src="/Content/Images/uploaded/2018_blog/jan10.jpg" alt="" width="100" /></p>";}i:79;a:5:{s:4:"guid";s:9:"Blog:4839";s:4:"link";s:69:"http://beatlesradio.com/the-beatles-50-years-ago-today-january-9-1968";s:5:"title";s:47:"The Beatles 50 Years Ago Today: January 9, 1968";s:11:"description";s:210:"<p><span class="st">JOHN-LENNON-Cover-by-Avedon-<em>The-BEATLES</em>-<wbr />Pullout-Poster.</span></p>
<p><span class="st"><img src="/Content/Images/uploaded/2018_blog/Jan9.jpg" alt="" width="100" /></span></p>";s:7:"summary";s:210:"<p><span class="st">JOHN-LENNON-Cover-by-Avedon-<em>The-BEATLES</em>-<wbr />Pullout-Poster.</span></p>
<p><span class="st"><img src="/Content/Images/uploaded/2018_blog/Jan9.jpg" alt="" width="100" /></span></p>";}i:80;a:5:{s:4:"guid";s:9:"Blog:4838";s:4:"link";s:69:"http://beatlesradio.com/the-beatles-50-years-ago-today-january-8-1968";s:5:"title";s:47:"The Beatles 50 Years Ago Today: January 8, 1968";s:11:"description";s:101:"<p>People in US were listening to <strong>Hello Goodbye</strong> by <strong>The Beatles.</strong></p>";s:7:"summary";s:101:"<p>People in US were listening to <strong>Hello Goodbye</strong> by <strong>The Beatles.</strong></p>";}i:81;a:5:{s:4:"guid";s:9:"Blog:4837";s:4:"link";s:69:"http://beatlesradio.com/the-beatles-50-years-ago-today-january-7-1968";s:5:"title";s:47:"The Beatles 50 Years Ago Today: January 7, 1968";s:11:"description";s:1380:"<h1 class="title single-title entry-title"><span style="font-size: 10pt;">Recording: Wonderwall Music by George Harrison</span></h1>
<p>EMI Recording Studio, Bombay, India<br />Producer: George Harrison<br />Engineers: JP Sen, SN Gupta</p>
<p>George Harrison had flown to India on 7 January 1968 to record the soundtrack for the film Wonderwall. The second session took place on this day.</p>
<p>The sessions began on 9 January in Bombay (Mumbai), and the soundtrack was mostly complete by 12 January.</p>
<p>On this day Harrison invited camera crews in to film proceedings. Reuters filmed around 45 seconds of colour footage, and BBC News shot slightly less. In the silent footage the musicians are believed to have been working on the track Fantasy Sequins.</p>
<p>The musicians included Ashish Khan (sarod), ahapurush Misra (tabla and pakavaj), Sharad Jadev and Hanuman Jadev (shanhais), Shambu-Das, Indril Bhattacharya and Shankar Ghosh (sitar), Chandra Shakher (sur-bahar), Shiv Kumar Sharmar (santorr), SR Kenkare and Hari Prasad Chaurasia (flute), Vinayak Vohra (taar shehnai) and Rijram Desad (dholak, harmonium and tabla-tarang).</p>
<p>The Bombay sessions took place at EMI Recording Studios, based at the Universal Insurance Building, Sir Pherozeshah Mehta Rd, Fort, Bombay 400001.</p>
